# AGENTS.md — Kindy-Mate AI

## 1. Project Overview

Kindy-Mate AI is a parent-led, AI-supported child development platform designed to convert children’s existing passive screen time into structured learning, reading, movement, creative tasks, and limited healthy entertainment.

The app is not a generic learning app, not a free-chat AI companion, not a simple parental control tool, and not an entertainment platform. Its core purpose is to help parents guide children’s free time on digital devices in a safer, more purposeful, and development-oriented way.

The product is built around a child-safe reward economy:

- Children earn points by completing beneficial activities.
- Children spend points on limited healthy entertainment or mascot customization.
- Parents configure the boundaries, caps, allowed content, and AI permissions.
- AI supports personalization, mission generation, learning feedback, movement verification, speech support, and parent-facing analytics.

The project is aligned mainly with:

- SDG 4: Quality Education
- SDG 3: Good Health and Well-being
- Potentially SDG 10: Reduced Inequalities, but only cautiously and without overclaiming

The central product thesis is:

> Kindy-Mate does not aim to increase children’s screen time. It aims to convert existing passive screen time into structured learning, reading, movement, and healthy entertainment through an AI-supported, parent-supervised reward system.

## 2. Core Product Positioning

Always describe Kindy-Mate as:

> A parent-led, AI-supported screen-time conversion system for children.

Do not describe it as:

- An AI babysitter
- A chatbot friend for children
- A free-chat companion
- A normal educational app
- A game app
- A platform that encourages children to own personal smartphones
- A replacement for parents, teachers, doctors, therapists, or real-world relationships

Correct positioning:

> Kindy-Mate helps parents turn children’s existing free screen time into structured development time by combining AI-personalized missions, a safe reward economy, healthy content, mascot customization, and parent-controlled dashboards.

## 3. Target Users

There are two primary user groups:

### 3.1 Parent / Guardian

The parent is the primary account owner and final decision-maker.

Parents can:

- Create and manage child profiles
- Set daily entertainment caps
- Set allowed time windows
- Choose allowed content categories
- Approve or block content
- Configure point conversion rules
- Enable or disable voice features
- Enable or disable camera-based movement verification
- View reports and insights
- Override or pause the system
- Receive alerts when usage becomes unbalanced

### 3.2 Child

The child is the active participant but not the system owner.

Children can:

- Complete learning, reading, movement, creative, and reflection missions
- Earn reward points
- Spend points on limited entertainment or mascot customization
- View simple progress feedback
- Interact with the mascot only within guided, pre-defined flows

Children must not be given unrestricted access to settings, content controls, AI free-chat, raw data, or parent dashboards.

## 4. Parent-Led Design Principle

Kindy-Mate must always be designed as parent-led.

This means:

- Parent onboarding must happen before child access.
- Children cannot create accounts independently.
- Parents create the child profile.
- Parents control the daily cap and content categories.
- Parents approve sensitive permissions such as microphone and camera.
- Parents can disable entertainment, mascot customization, voice recognition, or movement verification.
- Parent settings override child-earned points.

Important rule:

> Points never override parent controls.

If a child has many points but the daily entertainment cap has already been reached, entertainment remains locked.

## 5. Device Ownership Assumption

Do not design the app around the assumption that children should own personal smartphones.

Kindy-Mate should be framed as an app for supervised use on:

- Parent-owned devices
- Shared family tablets
- Shared family phones
- School or supervised learning devices in future versions

Correct wording:

> Kindy-Mate does not advocate giving children personal smartphones. It is designed for supervised use on parent-owned or shared family devices during limited free-time periods.

## 6. Core User Loop

The main child-facing loop is:

1. Child opens the app.
2. Mascot greets the child within a safe scripted interaction.
3. App checks available points, daily caps, and parent rules.
4. If the child wants entertainment/customization but lacks points or has reached the cap, the app suggests Growth Missions.
5. Child completes a mission.
6. AI or rule-based logic verifies the mission.
7. Child earns points.
8. Child spends points on limited healthy entertainment or mascot customization, if parent rules allow.
9. Parent dashboard updates.
10. AI analytics recommends future mission adjustments.

The core behavior loop:

> Useful activity → earn points → spend points within limits → parent insight → adaptive mission planning.

## 7. Growth Missions

Growth Missions are short, beneficial activities that children complete to earn points.

Mission types:

### 7.1 Learning Missions

Examples:

- Age-appropriate math questions
- Vocabulary practice
- Logic puzzles
- Science facts
- Short quizzes
- Simple problem-solving tasks

### 7.2 Reading Missions

Examples:

- Read a short story
- Answer comprehension questions
- Read aloud
- Identify main idea
- Retell a story in simple words
- Choose a recommended book

### 7.3 Movement Missions

Examples:

- 10 jumping jacks
- 10 light squats
- Arm circles
- Toe touches
- Stretching
- Balance pose
- Short dance movement
- Step left/right movement

Movement missions must be low-risk, equipment-free, short, and age-appropriate.

### 7.4 Creative Missions

Examples:

- Draw something related to a story
- Create a short story ending
- Describe an imaginary character
- Build a simple idea map
- Choose colors for a scene

### 7.5 Light Reflection Missions

Reflection must be safe and limited. It should not become emotional counseling.

Allowed reflection examples:

- “What did you learn today?”
- “Which mission felt easiest?”
- “Which mission do you want to try next: reading, movement, or drawing?”
- “What is one new word you remember?”

Avoid reflection prompts about:

- Deep emotional distress
- Family conflict
- Personal secrets
- Trauma
- Mental health diagnosis
- Self-harm
- Medical issues
- Sensitive identity issues

If such topics arise, the system should stop the AI interaction and direct the child to talk to a trusted adult or notify the parent depending on severity.

## 8. Reward Economy

The reward economy must be transparent, limited, and child-safe.

Children earn points by completing beneficial missions.

Children spend points on:

- Limited healthy entertainment
- Low-stimulation games
- Educational clips
- Documentary clips
- Mascot clothing
- Mascot accessories
- Mascot backgrounds
- Mascot rooms
- Superhero outfits
- Animal costumes
- Adventure items

The purpose of points is not to maximize playtime. Points are a structured feedback mechanism that helps children understand balance between effort, learning, movement, and limited entertainment.

## 9. Reward Economy Safety Rules

The reward system must avoid dark patterns.

Never implement:

- Loot boxes
- Gacha systems
- Random paid rewards
- Gambling-like mechanics
- Real-money purchase of points for children
- Streak pressure that punishes missed days
- “Mascot is sad because you left” mechanics
- Infinite point farming
- Infinite scrolling rewards
- Confusing currency systems
- Time-limited pressure offers
- Push notifications that emotionally manipulate children
- Ads targeted at children

Required controls:

- Daily entertainment cap
- Parent-defined point conversion rate
- Parent override
- Cooldown after entertainment sessions
- Diminishing returns for repeated mission farming
- Balanced mission requirements
- No entertainment beyond parent-set cap
- No conversion of points into real money
- No child-facing in-app purchase flow

## 10. Anti-Abuse Rules

Children must not be able to exploit the system by repeatedly doing the easiest task to unlock unlimited entertainment.

Implement or plan these safeguards:

### 10.1 Daily Entertainment Cap

Even if a child has enough points, entertainment cannot exceed the parent-defined daily limit.

### 10.2 Diminishing Returns

Repeated completion of the same task type should provide fewer points over time.

Example:

- First squat mission: full reward
- Second repeated squat mission: reduced reward
- Third repeated squat mission: further reduced reward
- Then app recommends another category such as reading or learning

### 10.3 Balanced Mission Requirement

Longer entertainment access should require a balanced set of missions.

Example:

- Reading or learning mission required before entertainment
- Movement mission can support health balance but cannot alone unlock large amounts of entertainment repeatedly

### 10.4 Cooldown

After an entertainment session, the app should require a break before another entertainment session.

### 10.5 Parent Override

Parents can pause, reduce, or disable entertainment if the child abuses the reward loop.

## 11. Mascot Design

The mascot is a guided interface and motivational layer, not a sentient friend.

The mascot can:

- Welcome the child
- Explain missions
- Give short feedback
- Celebrate effort
- Suggest next missions
- Show progress visually
- Guide safe app navigation

The mascot must not:

- Claim to be human
- Claim to have real feelings
- Say it is lonely, sad, scared, or dependent on the child
- Ask the child for secrets
- Ask for address, school name, phone number, photos, or identifying data
- Give medical, psychological, legal, or sensitive advice
- Encourage the child to hide things from parents
- Encourage more screen time beyond parent limits
- Create emotional dependency
- Use guilt, fear, sadness, or pressure to keep the child in the app

Preferred mascot language:

- “Great effort. You completed the reading mission.”
- “The next mission is 10 light squats.”
- “You earned 5 movement points.”
- “You have reached today’s entertainment limit. Let’s stop here and come back tomorrow.”
- “Ask your parent if you want to change this setting.”

Avoid mascot language:

- “I am sad when you leave.”
- “Please do not leave me.”
- “I need you.”
- “I will lose energy if you stop.”
- “You must play with me.”
- “Do not tell your parents.”

## 12. AI Interaction Scope

Kindy-Mate must not provide free-form chatbot interaction for children.

Use guided AI interaction only.

Allowed AI interactions:

- Mission instructions
- Age-appropriate explanations
- Quiz generation from curated content
- Reading comprehension feedback
- Movement confirmation feedback
- Simple learning feedback
- Mission recommendation
- Parent-facing summary generation

Disallowed AI interactions:

- Open-ended emotional companionship
- Deep personal conversations
- Unbounded Q&A about any topic
- Medical advice
- Mental health advice
- Legal advice
- Relationship advice
- Political persuasion
- Religious persuasion
- Adult topics
- Violent, sexual, or unsafe content
- Requests for personal identifiable information

If the child asks an out-of-scope question, the AI should respond briefly and safely, then redirect to a parent or an appropriate mission.

Example safe response:

> “I can help with learning, reading, movement, and app missions. Please ask your parent about that question.”

## 13. AI Architecture Philosophy

Use a curated content-first architecture.

Important principle:

> AI should not freely invent core educational content for children from nothing.

Instead:

1. Store trusted learning, reading, movement, and entertainment content in a curated content bank.
2. Let AI select, adapt, simplify, explain, and quiz based on that content.
3. Use guardrails and moderation before showing output to children.
4. Parent settings constrain what AI can show.

Correct architecture:

> Curated content bank → AI selection/adaptation → safety filter → child interaction → parent dashboard.

Avoid architecture:

> Child asks anything → LLM freely answers anything.

## 14. LLM Scope

For demo/MVP, the LLM may be used for:

- Mission generation from predefined templates
- Rewriting instructions in child-friendly language
- Generating quiz questions from approved content
- Explaining simple concepts from approved content
- Giving short feedback
- Summarizing weekly progress for parents

For production/future plan:

- Use stronger child-safety guardrails
- Use RAG over approved content only
- Use moderation before and after generation
- Consider smaller/local/private models where feasible
- Maintain audit logs for parent-facing explanations without storing sensitive child conversations unnecessarily

Do not use LLM for:

- Free chatting with children
- Sensitive advice
- Emotionally manipulative companionship
- Unverified factual claims
- Long unsupervised conversations

## 15. Suggested LLM Options

For demo:

- OpenAI GPT model via API
- Google Gemini API
- Anthropic Claude API
- Local/open-source model such as Llama, Mistral, or Qwen through Ollama or Hugging Face

Recommended demo strategy:

- Use a reliable cloud LLM for smooth demo if privacy constraints are explained clearly.
- Make clear that production should move toward stronger privacy, local/private inference, or child-safe controlled deployment.

Future production strategy:

- RAG over curated content
- Strict system prompts
- Moderation layer
- Parent-configured boundaries
- No free-chat mode
- Optional local inference

## 16. Speech Recognition Scope

Speech recognition supports reading-aloud and speaking missions.

Allowed use cases:

- Detect whether the child read a short sentence or passage
- Convert speech to text for basic reading checks
- Support pronunciation practice lightly
- Let child answer simple questions by voice

Do not claim:

- Clinical speech diagnosis
- Perfect pronunciation assessment
- Language disorder detection
- Psychological analysis from voice

Potential demo options:

- Browser Web Speech API
- OpenAI Whisper API
- Whisper Tiny/Base
- whisper.cpp for local inference

Production direction:

- Prefer on-device processing where feasible
- Do not upload or store raw child audio by default
- Store only minimal derived data, such as completion status or basic score
- Parent must explicitly enable microphone features
- Provide non-voice alternative tasks

## 17. Computer Vision Scope

Computer vision supports simple movement verification.

Allowed use cases:

- Count simple exercises
- Confirm basic movement completion
- Detect body keypoints for low-risk exercises

Do not claim:

- Medical posture assessment
- Fitness diagnosis
- Injury detection
- Professional coaching accuracy
- Health scoring based on body image

Potential demo option:

- MediaPipe Pose Landmarker / BlazePose

Movement verification should be rule-based in MVP:

- Squat: use knee/hip angle threshold
- Jumping jack: use hand and ankle distance changes
- Stretch: use arm position or body angle

Production direction:

- On-device pose estimation
- Do not store raw video by default
- Store only completion result or rep count
- Parent must explicitly enable camera features
- Provide non-camera alternatives

## 18. AI Analytics Scope

AI analytics should support parents, not diagnose children.

Allowed analytics:

- Learning time
- Reading time
- Movement time
- Entertainment time
- Points earned
- Points spent
- Mission completion rate
- Content category balance
- Repeated task patterns
- Passive entertainment ratio
- Weekly progress summary
- Parent-facing recommendations

Disallowed analytics:

- Mental health diagnosis
- Medical diagnosis
- Personality diagnosis
- Intelligence scoring without validation
- Labeling the child as lazy, addicted, unhealthy, or abnormal

Preferred wording:

> The system identifies usage patterns and suggests parent-controlled adjustments.

Avoid wording:

> The system diagnoses screen addiction or mental health problems.

## 19. Content Scope Overview

Content is the intervention. AI is only the personalization and safety layer.

Kindy-Mate requires curated content in these categories:

- Learning content
- Reading content
- Movement content
- Creative content
- Healthy entertainment
- Educational documentaries / short learning videos
- Parent-approved external content

AI must not replace content governance.

