## 28. Parent Alerts

Parent alerts may include:

- Entertainment cap reached
- Repeated attempts to unlock entertainment
- High passive entertainment ratio
- Low movement activity over several days
- Reading missions repeatedly skipped
- Attempted out-of-scope AI conversation
- Camera/microphone permission request
- New content approval required
- Bedtime usage attempt

Alerts should be informative, not alarmist.

Avoid language like:

- “Your child is addicted”
- “Your child is unhealthy”
- “Your child failed”

Use language like:

- “Entertainment time reached today’s limit.”
- “Reading missions were skipped three times this week.”
- “Consider setting a shorter entertainment window before bedtime.”

## 29. Privacy and Data Protection

Because the app targets children, privacy must be strict.

Core rules:

- Parent consent required before child use.
- Collect minimum data only.
- Use nickname/avatar instead of real name/photo by default.
- Do not ask for child address, school, phone number, or identifying details.
- Voice and camera features must be optional.
- Prefer on-device processing for audio/video.
- Do not upload raw audio/video by default.
- Do not sell child data.
- Do not show targeted ads.
- Do not create public child profiles.
- Parent can delete child data.
- Parent can export or review stored data.
- Store only what is necessary for mission progress and parental insight.

Sensitive data includes:

- Voice
- Face/body video
- Age
- Behavioral patterns
- Learning performance
- Usage history
- Emotional responses

Handle all such data carefully.

## 30. Safety and Moderation

The system should include:

- Input moderation
- Output moderation
- Topic restrictions
- PII detection
- Parent escalation
- Content whitelist
- Age-based filtering
- Blocked topics list
- Safe fallback responses

If AI is uncertain, it should not improvise freely. It should respond safely and redirect.

Example:

> “I cannot help with that. Please ask your parent. Let’s return to your reading mission.”

