## 36. Claims to Avoid

Do not claim:

- The app cures screen addiction.
- The app diagnoses mental health issues.
- The app guarantees academic improvement.
- The app replaces teachers.
- The app replaces parents.
- The app makes all screen time healthy.
- The app can safely let children use phones independently.
- The AI is always correct.
- The AI understands children emotionally.
- The mascot has real feelings.

Preferred claim style:

- “The app aims to support...”
- “The system helps parents...”
- “The design encourages...”
- “The platform can reduce passive consumption by...”
- “The MVP demonstrates...”

## 37. SDG Alignment

### SDG 4: Quality Education

Kindy-Mate supports SDG 4 by:

- Providing age-appropriate learning missions
- Encouraging reading
- Supporting literacy and numeracy activities
- Personalizing learning difficulty
- Turning passive screen time into active learning opportunities

### SDG 3: Good Health and Well-being

Kindy-Mate supports SDG 3 by:

- Encouraging movement breaks
- Reducing prolonged passive screen use
- Supporting healthier digital routines
- Allowing parent-set bedtime locks
- Helping balance screen-based activity with physical activity

### SDG 10: Reduced Inequalities

Use cautiously.

Kindy-Mate may support SDG 10 by:

- Helping busy families access structured learning support
- Offering low-cost educational guidance
- Supporting families that lack time to curate content manually

Do not overclaim that the app solves educational inequality.

## 38. Competition Narrative

The app should be presented as a sustainable development solution first, AI product second.

Narrative flow:

1. Problem: Children increasingly spend free time on passive, overstimulating digital content while parents lack time and tools to guide usage.
2. Gap: Existing parental controls block content but do not provide meaningful alternatives; educational apps teach but do not manage entertainment behavior; entertainment apps maximize engagement rather than development.
3. Solution: Kindy-Mate converts existing screen time into structured learning, reading, movement, and limited healthy entertainment through a parent-controlled reward system.
4. AI role: AI personalizes missions, explains learning content, verifies movement/reading, and summarizes progress for parents.
5. SDG impact: Supports quality education and child well-being by improving the quality and structure of children’s digital time.

